{{Infobox organization |name = Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs |image_border = |image = Belfer_Center.JPG |caption = The Belfer Center is located within the [[Harvard Kennedy School]] |formation = 1973 |type = [[Think tank]] |headquarters = 79 John F. Kennedy Street |location = [[Cambridge, MA|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S. |leader_title = Director |leader_name = [[Ashton Carter]] |website = [http://belfercenter.org www.belfercenter.org] }} The '''Robert and Renée Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs''' (also known as the '''Belfer Center''') is a permanent research center located within the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]]. Since 2017, the center is led by Director [[Ash Carter]], former US Secretary of Defense and Co-Director Eric Rosenbach, former Assistant Secretary of Defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfercenter.org/about|title=About|website=Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs}}</ref>
Belfer was founded in 1973<ref>[http://www.isn.ethz.ch/Digital-Library/Organizations/Detail/?id=165758 Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs (BCSIA)], International Relations and Security Network (ISN), Zurich</ref> by biochemist [[Paul M. Doty]] as the 'Program for Science and International Affairs' within [[Harvard Faculty of Arts and Sciences|Harvard's Faculty of Arts and Sciences]]<ref>[http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/obituaries/articles/2011/12/06/paul_doty_91_presidential_adviser_on_nuclear_arms_control/ Bryan Marquard & staff, Obituary: "Paul Doty, 91, presidential adviser on nuclear arms control"], ''[[Boston Globe]],'' 6 December 2011</ref> to provide analysis on [[arms control]] and nuclear threat reduction. Following a grant from the [[Ford Foundation]], the program was re-established as the Center for Science and International Affairs, becoming the first permanent research center at the newly formed School of Government. In 1997, following further endowment, the center was renamed as the '''Robert and Renée Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs''' in honor of Robert A. Belfer, founder of Belco Oil & Gas Corporation.
In 2012, the [[Stanton Foundation]] provided funds for a paid [[Wikipedian in residence]] at the Belfer Center. This became controversial due to links between the Belfer Center and the Stanton Foundation (the directors of each are a married couple) and public concerns about [[conflict-of-interest editing on Wikipedia]].<ref name="Daily Dot Belfer">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailydot.com/business/wikipedia-paid-editing-scandal-stanton/ |title=One of Wikimedia's largest donors accused in paid editing scandal |publisher=[[The Daily Dot]] |author=Tim Sampson |date=14 April 2014}}</ref> The center is organized into subgroups with specific areas of focus; for example, an [[energy technology]] innovation policy group led by [[Laura Diaz Anadon]].<ref name="twsScienceMag">{{cite web | url= http://news.sciencemag.org/2011/10/super-science-suggestions-house-panel-lays-out-spending-preferences | title= Super Science Suggestions: House Panel Lays Out Spending Preferences | publisher= Science Magazine | date= 17 October 2011 | accessdate= Sep 14, 2014 | quote=...Laura Diaz Anadon, a chemical engineer and director of the energy technology innovation policy group at the Harvard Kennedy School of Government.... | author= Science News Staff }}</ref><ref name="twsEnergyCollective">{{cite web | url= http://theenergycollective.com/jessejenkins/205481/friday-energy-facts-how-much-water-does-fracking-shale-gas-consume | title= Energy Facts: How Much Water Does Fracking for Shale Gas Consume? | publisher= The Energy Collective | date= April 6, 2013 | accessdate= Sep 14, 2014 | quote=...how much water does shale gas consume per unit of energy produced...a 2010 paper by ...Laura Diaz Anadon... of Harvard’s Belfer Center has data on exactly that question ... | author= Jesse Jenkins }}</ref>
== Board members == Center board members include: * [[Lewis M. Branscomb]], Professor emeritus of Public Policy and Corporate Management * [[Albert Carnesale]], former Harvard University [[Provost (education)|provost]] * [[Ashton Carter|Ashton B. Carter]], Chair of International Relations, Security & Science faculty, physicist, who served as the 25th [[United States Secretary of Defense]] * [[John M. Deutch]], former [[Director of Central Intelligence]] * [[John P. Holdren]], John Heinz Professor of Environmental Policy * [[Joseph Nye]], University Distinguished Service Professor
== Advisory board == The center has an international advisory board. Members include<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfercenter.org/about/international-council|title=International Council|website=Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs}}</ref>: * [[Michael Chertoff]], former U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security * [[Gregory C. Carr]], Boston Technology founder * [[Tim Collins (financier)|Tim Collins]], [[Ripplewood Holdings]] founder * [[Chuck Robbins]], CEO of Cisco Systems * [[Nathaniel Philip Rothschild|Nathaniel Rothschild]], Atticus Capital co-chairman * [[Paul Volcker]], former United States Chairman of the Federal Reserve
== Past notable members == * [[Stephen Biddle]], theorist setting U.S. counterinsurgency policy
