{{other people}} {{Infobox writer | image = Manning_in_2008.jpg | imagesize = 150px | name = Richard Manning | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|02|07}} | birth_place = [[Flint, Michigan]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Author, journalist | nationality = United States | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | website = <!-- http://www.goodworksintrauma.org/ --> }}
'''Richard "Dick" Manning''' is an environmental author and journalist, with particular interest in the history and future of the American [[prairie]], agriculture and poverty. He writes frequently about trauma and poverty for the National Native Children's Trauma Center based at the University of Montana, where he is a senior research associate. He is the author of eight books, and his articles have been published in ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', ''Audubon''<ref name="commondreams">[http://www.commondreams.org/views02/0201-05.htm Mountains, Elk, and Sprawl<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713011717/http://www.commondreams.org/views02/0201-05.htm |date=July 13, 2007 }}</ref> and ''[[The Bloomsbury Review]]''.<ref name="penguingroup">{{cite web|url=http://www.penguin.com/author/richard-manning/243205 |title=Richard Manning |website=Penguin Random House|accessdate=2015-08-20}}</ref>
==Life== Manning worked as a journalist, reporter and editor for more than 30 years,<ref>[http://www.austincollege.edu/NewsDetail.asp?NewsID=345&ItemID=3482 Austin College. Sherman, Texas<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060914221440/http://www.austincollege.edu/NewsDetail.asp?NewsID=345&ItemID=3482 |date=September 14, 2006 }}</ref> including four years at the ''[[Missoulian]]''.<ref name="penguingroup"/> In 1995 he was the recipient of a [[John S. Knight Fellowship]] from [[Stanford University]].<ref name="stanford">{{cite web|url=http://knight.stanford.edu/fellows/1995/ |title=Meet the Fellows &#124; JSK &#124; Knight Fellowships Class of 1995 |publisher=knight.stanford.edu|accessdate=2015-08-20}}</ref> He is a three-time winner of the ''[[Seattle Times]]'' [[C.B. Blethen Award for Investigative Journalism]], and has also won the [[Audubon Society]] Journalism Award and the inaugural [[Richard J. Margolis]] Award<ref>[http://www.margolis.com/award/html/1992_-_richard_manning.html 1992 - Richard Manning<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626081123/http://www.margolis.com/award/html/1992_-_richard_manning.html |date=June 26, 2007 }}</ref> in 1992.
He lives in [[Lolo, Montana]]<ref name="penguingroup" /> with his wife, Tracy Stone-Manning.
